<div class="page-title">Article</div>
<div class="news-article">
  <div class="masthead">The Public Record</div>
  <div class="section-tag">Climate &middot; Mind &amp; Behavior</div>
  <h1 class="headline">Why Humans Are Built to Solve Climate Change</h1>
  <div class="byline">By Andrew Miller &middot; Published April 22, 2025 &middot; 3 min read</div>
  <div class="article-body">
    <p>When David Smith, a Nobel Prize-winning economist, was asked whether humanity could solve the climate crisis, he didn't flinch. "There is no reason to believe that humans cannot cooperate at the scale this problem demands," he said. "We have done it before, and we are doing it now, in thousands of communities, all over the world."</p>
    <p>Experts argue that humans possess a unique and powerful ability that no other species comes close to: we can feel genuine concern for people we have never met, in places we have never been, facing problems that haven't happened yet. And when we choose to direct that concern, we are capable of sustaining it across years, decades, even generations. Climate change, in that sense, may be exactly the kind of challenge that brings out the best of what makes us human.</p>
    <p>Unlike every other species on Earth, humans don't just react to the world, we imagine it. Psychologists call this "mental time travel": our ability to picture futures we've never seen and work backwards to make them better. It is the same ability that led doctors to develop vaccines before outbreaks became unstoppable, and engineers to build flood defences for storms that hadn't yet arrived.</p>
    <p>When 197 countries gathered in 1987 to ban the chemicals destroying the ozone layer, we weren't responding to a disaster we could see or feel. The threat was invisible, global, and decades away from its worst consequences. By every measure, it was exactly the kind of crisis that critics said could never be solved. And yet we acted and succeeded, because scientists told a clear story, leaders listened, and people decided that the future was worth protecting.</p>
    <p>Climate change is exactly the kind of slow, distributed challenge humans have solved before. We eradicated smallpox. We repaired the ozone layer. We phased out leaded gasoline. None of those threats stood in front of us either.</p>
    <p>We are not a species looking the other way. We are a species still deciding how fast to move, and history suggests that when we do decide, we are capable of moving fast.</p>
    <p>That might be the most human thing of all.</p>
  </div>
</div>
